    {
      "id": "a1000000-0000-4000-8000-0000000000f0",
      "name": "Sticky Note Overview",
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        -620,
        -40
      ],
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## Sync Asana project tasks to a Google Sheet mirror\n\n### How it works\n\n1. On a schedule, the workflow reads every task in one Asana project with its status, assignee, due date and section.\n2. It reads the current sheet, then diffs by task GID: tasks still in Asana are upserted, and rows whose task is gone are flagged `present` = `No`.\n3. The sheet becomes an always-current mirror you can pivot and filter, and no row is ever hard-deleted.\n\n### Setup steps\n\n- [ ] Add an Asana Personal Access Token as a Bearer Auth credential and select it on `Fetch Asana Tasks`.\n- [ ] Add your Google Sheets credential and pick your spreadsheet and `Tasks` tab on the three Google Sheets nodes.\n- [ ] In `Set Sync Config`, set `asana_project_gid`, `sheet_id` and `sheet_tab`.\n- [ ] Add a header row to the tab: gid, name, assignee, section, due_on, completed, permalink, modified_at, synced_at, present.\n\n### Customization\n\nChange the schedule interval to sync more or less often. Optionally feed the run-summary counts to a Groq node for a one-line note on what changed; the mirror stays deterministic and the model never touches row data.",
        "width": 520,
        "height": 560
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "a1000000-0000-4000-8000-0000000000f1",
      "name": "Sticky Note Configure",
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        -40,
        8
      ],
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## Configure the sync\n\nSet the schedule, the Asana project GID and the target Sheet ID and tab in one place.",
        "color": 7,
        "width": 400,
        "height": 264
      }
    },
